04742nam a22005535i 9780822384861DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20032003ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223848617 a10.1515/97808223848612doi  a(DE-B1597)552918  a(OCoLC)1058440959  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPN1995.9.A8bA28 2003 7aSOC0520002bisacsh04a302.23432211 aAcland, Charles R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aScreen Traffic :bMovies, Multiplexes, and Global Culture /cCharles R. Acland. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2003] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (352 p.) :b16 illus., 34 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tList of Tables and Figures -- tAcknowledgments -- tI. THEORIZING CONTEMPORARY CINEMAGOING -- t1. Global Audiences and the Current Cinema -- t2. Traveling Cultures, Mutating Commodities -- t3. Matinees, Summers, and the Practice of Cinemagoing -- tII. STRUCTURES OF CINEMATIC EXPERIENCE -- t4. Crisis and Settlement in Exhibition and Distribution -- t5. ''Here Come the Megaplexes,'' -- t6. Zones and Speeds of International Cinematic Life -- t7. Northern Screens -- t8. The Miniaturization of the Theme Park, or After the ''Death'' of Cinema -- t9. Cinemagoing as ''Felt Internationalism,'' -- tAPPENDICES -- t1. Screens per Million Population -- t2. World Screen Count -- t3. National Average Cinema Admissions per Person (annual) -- t4. Multiplexing in Europe -- t5. MPAA's Goals for Digital Cinema -- t6. Existing Digital Cinemas, 2000 -- t7. Digital Movies Released for DLP Projectors -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Screen Traffic, Charles R. Acland examines how, since the mid-1980s, the U.S. commercial movie business has altered conceptions of moviegoing both within the industry and among audiences. He shows how studios, in their increasing reliance on revenues from international audiences and from the ancillary markets of television, videotape, DVD, and pay-per-view, have cultivated an understanding of their commodities as mutating global products. Consequently, the cultural practice of moviegoing has changed significantly, as has the place of the cinema in relation to other sites of leisure.Integrating film and cultural theory with close analysis of promotional materials, entertainment news, trade publications, and economic reports, Acland presents an array of evidence for the new understanding of movies and moviegoing that has developed within popular culture and the entertainment industry. In particular, he dissects a key development: the rise of the megaplex, characterized by large auditoriums, plentiful screens, and consumer activities other than film viewing. He traces its genesis from the re-entry of studios into the movie exhibition business in 1986 through 1998, when reports of the economic destabilization of exhibition began to surface, just as the rise of so-called e-cinema signaled another wave of change. Documenting the current tendency toward an accelerated cinema culture, one that appears to arrive simultaneously for everyone, everywhere, Screen Traffic unearths and critiques the corporate and cultural forces contributing to the "felt internationalism" of our global era.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aCulture in motion pictures. 0aMotion picture audiences. 0aMotion picturesxDistribution. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822384861zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822384861423Cover